The answer is $2/3$. 

By AM-GM, we have
\begin{align*}
2^{n+1}(a_1\cdots a_n)^{1/n} &= \left((4a_1)(4^2a_2)\cdots (4^na_n)\right)^{1/n}\\
& \leq \frac{\sum_{k=1}^n (4^k a_k)}{n}.
\end{align*}
Thus
\begin{align*}
2S &\leq \sum_{n=1}^\infty \frac{\sum_{k=1}^n (4^k a_k)}{4^n} \\
&= \sum_{n=1}^\infty \sum_{k=1}^n (4^{k-n}a_k) = \sum_{k=1}^\infty \sum_{n=k}^\infty (4^{k-n}a_k) \\
&= \sum_{k=1}^\infty \frac{4a_k}{3}  = \frac{4}{3}
\end{align*}
and $S \leq 2/3$. Equality is achieved when $a_k=\frac{3}{4^k}$ for all $k$, since in this case $4a_1=4^2a_2=\cdots=4^na_n$ for all $n$.

descriptive_long.solution:
The answer is $2/3$. 

By AM-GM, we have
\begin{align*}
2^{loopvarn+1}(seqelemone\cdots seqelemind)^{1/loopvarn} &= \left((4seqelemone)(4^2seqelemtwo)\cdots (4^{loopvarn}seqelemind)\right)^{1/loopvarn}\\
& \leq \frac{\sum_{loopvark=1}^{loopvarn} (4^{loopvark} seqelemvar)}{loopvarn}.
\end{align*}
Thus
\begin{align*}
2summax &\leq \sum_{loopvarn=1}^\infty \frac{\sum_{loopvark=1}^{loopvarn} (4^{loopvark} seqelemvar)}{4^{loopvarn}} \\
&= \sum_{loopvarn=1}^\infty \sum_{loopvark=1}^{loopvarn} (4^{loopvark-loopvarn}seqelemvar) = \sum_{loopvark=1}^\infty \sum_{loopvarn=loopvark}^\infty (4^{loopvark-loopvarn}seqelemvar) \\
&= \sum_{loopvark=1}^\infty \frac{4seqelemvar}{3}  = \frac{4}{3}
\end{align*}
and $summax \leq 2/3$. Equality is achieved when $seqelemvar=\frac{3}{4^{loopvark}}$ for all $loopvark$, since in this case $4seqelemone=4^2seqelemtwo=\cdots=4^{loopvarn}seqelemind$ for all $loopvarn$.

descriptive_long_confusing.solution:
The answer is $2/3$. 

By AM-GM, we have
\begin{align*}
2^{latitude+1}(pineapple\cdots cranberry)^{1/latitude} &= \left((4pineapple)(4^2strawberry)\cdots (4^{latitude}cranberry)\right)^{1/latitude}\\
& \leq \frac{\sum_{altitude=1}^{latitude} (4^{altitude} raspberry)}{latitude}.
\end{align*}
Thus
\begin{align*}
2quadratic &\leq \sum_{latitude=1}^\infty \frac{\sum_{altitude=1}^{latitude} (4^{altitude} raspberry)}{4^{latitude}} \\
&= \sum_{latitude=1}^\infty \sum_{altitude=1}^{latitude} (4^{altitude-latitude}raspberry) = \sum_{altitude=1}^\infty \sum_{latitude=altitude}^\infty (4^{altitude-latitude}raspberry) \\
&= \sum_{altitude=1}^\infty \frac{4raspberry}{3}  = \frac{4}{3}
\end{align*}
and $quadratic \leq 2/3$. Equality is achieved when $raspberry=\frac{3}{4^{altitude}}$ for all $altitude$, since in this case $4pineapple=4^2strawberry=\cdots=4^{latitude}cranberry$ for all $latitude$.

descriptive_long_misleading.solution:
The answer is $2/3$. 

By AM-GM, we have
\begin{align*}
2^{terminal+1}(emptyone\cdots emptyitem)^{1/terminal} &= \left((4emptyone)(4^2emptytwo)\cdots (4^{terminal}emptyitem)\right)^{1/terminal}\\
& \leq \frac{\sum_{beginning=1}^{terminal} (4^{beginning} vacantterm)}{terminal}.
\end{align*}
Thus
\begin{align*}
2minimumdifference &\leq \sum_{terminal=1}^\infty \frac{\sum_{beginning=1}^{terminal} (4^{beginning-terminal}vacantterm)}{4^{terminal}} \\
&= \sum_{terminal=1}^\infty \sum_{beginning=1}^{terminal} (4^{beginning-terminal}vacantterm) = \sum_{beginning=1}^\infty \sum_{terminal=beginning}^\infty (4^{beginning-terminal}vacantterm) \\
&= \sum_{beginning=1}^\infty \frac{4vacantterm}{3}  = \frac{4}{3}
\end{align*}
and $minimumdifference \leq 2/3$. Equality is achieved when $vacantterm=\frac{3}{4^{beginning}}$ for all $beginning$, since in this case $4emptyone=4^2emptytwo=\cdots=4^{terminal}emptyitem$ for all $terminal$.

